ns and more, offering a practical yet elegant blueprint for a modernized system of money and banking—one that, crucially, can be accomplished through incremental changes to the United States’ current system. He brings a critical, missing dimension to the ongoing debates over financial stability policy, arguing that the issue is primarily one of monetary system design. The Money Problem offers a way to mitigate the risk of catastrophic panic in the future, and it will expand the financial reform conversation in the United States and abroad.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aBanks and bankingzUnited States. 0aFinancial crisesxPrevention. 0aInformal sector (Economics)zUnited States. 0aMonetary policyzUnited States. 0aMoney marketzUnited States. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh  afinance, monetary, funds, funding, money, economy, economics, regulation, regulating, financial, crisis, analysis, public, private, stability, wealth, income, institutional, institutions, question, modern, banking, contemporary, banks, united states, usa, america, reform, change, policy, theory, theoretical, prevention, sector, experiment.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311071098440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226330464423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226330464/original  a978-3-11-071098-4  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles